{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509262"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:15:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:15:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11410"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11410"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.04,0.8,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101786"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4046"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84242"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2757"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42594"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101786"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of progressively worsening fatigue and dyspnoea on exertion. His medical history includes gout, hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia and a STEMI seven months ago, managed with a drug-eluting stent. His current medications include perindopril, atorvastatin, allopurinol and aspirin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears tired but alert. His pulse rate is 46/min, blood pressure 118/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. On close examination of the JVP, cannon a-waves are observed. Heart sounds are normal with no murmurs. Chest is clear to auscultation. An ECG shows complete dissociation between P waves and QRS complexes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atropine","DC cardioversion","Permanent pacemaker","Transcutaneous pacing","Isoprenaline infusion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms, previous history of myocardial infarction, bradycardia, and cannon a waves in the JVP are consistent with third-degree (complete) AV block. The ECG confirms this with complete dissociation between P waves and QRS complexes. In complete heart block, the atria and ventricles beat independently of each other, as the electrical impulses from the atria cannot reach the ventricles due to a complete block at the AV node or His-Purkinje system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermanent pacemaker\u003C/strong\u003E implantation is the definitive management for third-degree AV block in a hemodynamically stable patient, particularly when there are no reversible causes identified. This patient\u0027s history of previous myocardial infarction suggests the AV block is likely due to ischemic damage to the conduction system. A permanent pacemaker provides reliable ventricular pacing to maintain adequate cardiac output and prevent Stokes-Adams attacks (syncope due to periods of asystole).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtropine\u003C/strong\u003E is a temporary measure used in hemodynamically unstable patients with AV block. It works by blocking parasympathetic influence on the AV node, potentially increasing conduction. However, it is ineffective in infranodal blocks (which are common after myocardial infarction) and provides only transient benefit. It is not a definitive management strategy for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDC cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E is used to terminate tachyarrhythmias such as atrial fibrillation, atrial flutter, or ventricular tachycardia. It has no role in the management of bradyarrhythmias like complete heart block and would be inappropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscutaneous pacing\u003C/strong\u003E is a temporary emergency measure for hemodynamically unstable patients with symptomatic bradycardia until more definitive therapy can be instituted. It involves placing external pads on the chest and back to deliver electrical impulses to pace the heart. While effective as a bridge, it is uncomfortable for conscious patients and not suitable as definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsoprenaline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-adrenergic agonist that can temporarily increase heart rate in bradyarrhythmias. However, it increases myocardial oxygen demand and can worsen ischemia, particularly concerning in a patient with recent STEMI. It is only used as a temporary measure in specific circumstances when other options are not available, and is not appropriate as definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Third-degree (complete) atrioventricular block is characterized by complete dissociation between atrial and ventricular activity, often with cannon a waves visible in the JVP.","Permanent pacemaker implantation is the definitive management for third-degree AV block without reversible causes.","Temporary pacing measures are reserved for hemodynamically unstable patients until definitive management can be implemented."],"references":["Tung, MKY \u0026 Healy, S 2016, \u0027Cannon A Waves\u0027, New England Journal of medicine vol. 374, no. 4, p. e4. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26816027/","Knabben V, Chhabra L, Slane M. Third-Degree Atrioventricular Block. Treasure Island. Updated 2022 May 22. Accessed October 5, 2022. .https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545199/#_article-17971_s8_","Sauer WH. Third-degree (complete) atrioventricular block. UpToDate. Updated September 12, 2022. Accessed October 5, 2022. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/third-degree-complete-atrioventricular-block?search=third%20degree%20heart%20block\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H6"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84242"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11410"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18937"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18937"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ab893507-3406-48e2-a432-00b647922e9d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ab893507-3406-48e2-a432-00b647922e9d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84242"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T14:20:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-04T14:21:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4046"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101786"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e